innerley, Shropshire, England":"Kinnerley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Manley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places in Devon and Cheshire, named in Old English as ‘common wood or clearing’, from <i>(ge)mǣne</i> ‘common, shared’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The surname is still chiefly found in the regions around these villages.","English: nickname from Middle English<i>mannly</i> ‘manly, virile, brave’ (Old English<i>mannlīc</i>, originally ‘man-like’).","Irish (County Cork): Anglicized form of <b>Ó Máinle</b> (and often pronounced <i>Mauly</i>), of unexplained etymology. Compare   Malley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Munley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Manley  . This surname is rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in eastern Scotland."]},{"name":"Malley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Malley  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in northern France called Mailly (Marne, Somme, and elsewhere).","Americanized form of Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Mlej</b> (see   Malay  )."]},{"name":"McMonagle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cahal.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Maonghaile</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Maonghal</i>, composed of the elements <i>maoin</i> ‘wealth’ + <i>gal</i> ‘valor’. In this form the consonant cluster <i>-ngh-</i> has been ‘delenited’. Compare   Manley   4, which is based on an earlier form of the genitive."]},{"name":"Minkley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Arno.","English (East Midlands): perhaps a variant of   Manley   with intrusive <i>-k-</i>.","Possibly also an Americanized form of German   Minkler  ."]},{"name":"Munnelly","meanings":["Irish (Mayo): variant of   Manley  ."]},{"name":"Manly","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Manley  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":6,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":16,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Manley was born about 1090, in Cheshire, England as the daughter of Sir Roger de Manley Knight and Mrs Roger de Manley. She had at least 1 son with Iorwerth Goch ap Maredudd."},"et":{"about 1090–":"umbes 1090–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1110–1171":"1110–1171","1080–1171":"1080–1171","1150–1221":"1150–1221","1110–1194":"1110–1194","1070–1135":"1070–1135","–Female":"Surnud","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1090":"1090","about 1090":"umbes 1090","1135":"1135","1221":"1221","1110":"1110","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1194":"1194","1171":"1171","1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cae Howel, Kinnerley, Shropshire, England":"Kinnerley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"about 1090–":"noin 1090–Kuollut","1090–Female":"1090–Kuollut","1110–1171":"1110–1171","1080–1171":"1080–1171","1150–1221":"1150–1221","1110–1194":"1110–1194","1070–1135":"1070–1135","–Female":"Kuollut","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1090":"1090","about 1090":"noin 1090","1135":"1135","1221":"1221","1110":"1110","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1194":"1194","1171":"1171","1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cae Howel, Kinnerley, Shropshire, England":"Kinnerley, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"about 1090–":"environ 1090–Décédée","1090–Female":"1090–Décédée","1110–1171":"1110–1171","1080–1171":"1080–1171","1150–1221":"1150–1221","1110–1194":"1110–1194","1070